<p><strong>Western Fence Lizard (<em>Sceloporus occidentalis</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Iguanidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Sceloporus occidentalis</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>Western Fence Lizard<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p> The Western Fence Lizard has a body length of 2¼-3½ inches. It has a black, gray or brown coloring with a blotched pattern. It is longitudinally dark-striped, sides of belly are blue, and rear surfaces of limbs are yellow or orange. Its dorsal scales are keeled and pointed; males have enlarged tails and a blue patch on the throat; females no blue or green above, but have dark crescents or bars on the back. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.californiaherps.com/lizards/pages/s.o.occidentalis.html">California Herps</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>This lizard is one of the most common western lizards seen on fenceposts, rocks, logs, piles of lumber, and on sides of buildings. It occupies a variety of habitats including grasslands, broken chaparral, sagebrush, woodlands, open coniferous forests, and farmlands. It occasionally climbs trees, but is more often found on or near ground. It eats small invertebrates such as spiders, crickets, ticks, and scorpions, and occasionally small lizards including its own species. Females lay clutches of 3-17 eggs between April-July.</p>
